ss a traditional Japanese wedding here. The forest surrounding the shrine is believed to bring about good fortune.\n\nEmperor Meiji, after whom an entire era of Japanese history is called, lead the nation into a period of a dramatic modernization in the 19th century. Under his rule, Japan took over many Western inventions, ended the 250 years long period of closed borders policy, reformed its military system and government and rapidly started to emerge as one of the advanced nations of the age.\n\nThe complex is separated from the city by a great forest created by hundreds of thousands of trees that were donated by people from all over the country, to protect the deified spirits of Emperor Meiji and the Empress Dowager. \n\nSince 2016, the shrine is undergoing a reconstruction. It is still open to visitors, though.","provider":null,"translation_provider":null,"link":null,"is_translated":true},"opening_hours_raw":null,"media_count":23,"main_media":{"usage":{"square":"m:32577885","video_preview":null,"portrait":"m:32577884","landscape":"m:32577885"},"media":[{"original":{"size":null,"width":3072,"height":2040},"suitability":["landscape","square"],"url_template":"https://media-cdn.sygictraveldata.com/media/{size}/612664395a40232133447d33247d383332353737383835","created_at":"2016-11-08T10:23:09+0000","source":{"provider":"wikipedia","name":"Wikimedia Commons","external_id":null},"type":"photo","created_by":"56d5ac07b3881","url":"https://media-cdn.sygictraveldata.com/media/612664395a40232133447d33247d383332353737383835.jpg","quadkey":null,"attribution":{"title_url":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Meiji_Jingu_006.jpg","license":"CC0","other":null,"author_url":"http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/User:Ocdp","author":"Ocdp","title":"明治神宮の神門","license_url":"http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/deed.en"},"location":null,"id":"m:32577885"},{"original":{"size":null,"width":3072,"height":2304},"suitability":["square","portrait"],"url_template":"https://media-cdn.sygictraveldata.com/media/{size}/612664395a40232133447d33247d383332353737383834","created_at":"2016-11-08T10:23:07+0000","source":{"provider":"wikipedia","name":"Wikimedia Commons","external_id":null},"type":"photo","created_by":"56d5ac07b3881","url":"https://media-cdn.sygictraveldata.com/media/612664395a40232133447d33247d383332353737383834.jpg","quadkey":null,"attribution":{"title_url":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Meiji-jingu_shinmon2.jpg","license":"CC-BY-SA-3.0","other":null,"author_url":null,"author":"KENPEI","title":"明治神宮　神門","license_url":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/"},"location":null,"id":"m:32577884"}]},"references":[{"id":1479970,"title":"Wikipedia","type":"wiki","language_id":"en","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiji_Shrine","supplier":"wiki","priority":0,"currency":null,"price":null,"flags":[]},{"id":13297501,"title":"Official Website","type":"link:official","language_id":null,"url":"http://www.meijijingu.or.jp/","supplier":null,"priority":0,"currency":null,"price":null,"flags":[]}],"external_ids":[{"id":"way:469908925","type":"osm","language_id":null},{"id":"Q287165","type":"wikidata","language_id":null},{"id":"en:Meiji Shrine","type":"wikipedia","language_id":"en"}],"collection_count":0,"satellite":null},{"id":"poi:19849","level":"poi","rating":1.0385204112169,"rating_local":2.407402211662989,"quadkey":"133002112312012023202","location":{"lat":35.6621303,"lng":139.7694811},"bounding_box":{"south":35.6595655,"west":139.7659122,"north":35.6646564,"east":139.7732099},"name":"Tsukiji Fish Market","name_suffix":"Tokyo, Japan","original_name":"築地市場","url":"https://go.sygic.com/travel/place?id=poi:19849","duration":1800,"marker":"eating:restaurant:asian:japanese","categories":["eating","shopping"],"parent_ids":["city:865324","city:846468","city:864790","city:767081","poi:36579807","city:2585","region:2009424","poi:36125237","poi:36368651","country:75","continent:4"],"perex":"This market is the largest and busiest wholesale fish and seafood market in the world.","customer_rating":null,"star_rating":null,"star_rating_unofficial":null,"thumbnail_url":"https://media-cdn.sygictraveldata.com/media/poi:19849","tags":[{"key":"Japanese Cuisine","name":"Japanese Cuisine"},{"key":"Fish Market","name":"Fish Market"},{"key":"Free","name":"Free"}],"area":126616,"address":"1 Tsukiji, 104-0045, 中央区","admission":"Free admission.","email":null,"opening_hours":"The inner market of Tsukiji Market closed on October 6, 2018 and moved to a new site in Toyosu where it reopened as Toyosu Market. Tsukiji\'s outer market, on the other hand, did not close and will remain in business.\n\nOpen hours vary from shop to shop, typically from 5 am to 2 pm.","is_deleted":false,"phone":"+81 3 3542 1111","description":{"text":"This market is the largest and busiest wholesale fish and seafood market in the world. Spreading over what used to be a quiet upper-class residential area, the fish market only moved to Tsukiji after an earthquake in 1923. It opened in 1935 and many of the buildings from that era are still standing and are in use today.\n\nPopular with locals and tourists alike, it is the place to enjoy the lively atmosphere of a Japanese culinary hotspot. If you want to buy some fresh food including vegetables and traditional Japanese foodstuffs, head here. You can also take a break from the shopping in one of the local restaurants - they offer excellent sushi. \n\nWhen visiting, remember not to bargain with the sellers, as this is considered very rude. Also, if you are willing to get up early and register at 4:30 am, you can go and take part in the 5 am live tuna auction. \n\nTourists are only admitted to the following sections: the Seafood Wholesale, the Vegetable and Fruit Wholesale, the restaurants and the Outside Market.","provider":null,"translation_provider":null,"link":null,"is_translated":true},"opening_hours_raw":null,"media_count":19,"main_media":{"usage":{"square":"m:2663853","video_preview":null,"po